    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "but youre saying secular equality \"must take precedence\" because it protects everyone. what about the person whose religious freedom is being violated by that same law? to them, the state isn't being neutral, it's actually being coercive by forcing them to act against their faith. isn't it just as much of a \"right\" to be free from state interference in your conscience as it is to have civil protections? why is one viewed as more fundamental than the other?",
